06919nam a22008895i 9781782381655DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20012001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823816557 a10.1515/97817823816552doi  a(DE-B1597)635700  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6322.7b.I5 2001 7aPOL0610002bisacsh04a291.1a291.1783315100aIn God's Name :bGenocide and Religion in the Twentieth Century /ced. by Omer Bartov, Phyllis Mack. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWar and Genocide ;v400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I – The Perpetrators: Theology and Practice -- tChapter 1 Religion, Ethnicity, and Nationalism: Armenians, Turks, and the End of the Ottoman Empire -- tChapter 2 Genocide, Religion, and Gerhard Kittel: Protestant Theologians Face the Third Reich -- tChapter 3 When Jesus Was an Aryan: The Protestant Church and Antisemitic Propaganda -- tChapter 4 A Pure Conscience Is Good Enough: Bishop von Galen and Resistance to Nazism -- tChapter 5 Between God and Hitler: German Military Chaplains and the Crimes of the Third Reich -- tChapter 6 Christian Churches and Genocide in Rwanda -- tChapter 7 The Churches and the Genocide in the East African Great Lakes Region -- tChapter 8 Kosovo Mythology and the Bosnian Genocide -- tII. Survival: Rescuers and Victims -- tChapter 9 The Absorption of Armenian Women and Children into Muslim Households As a Structural Component of the Armenian Genocide -- tChapter 10 Transcending Boundaries: Hungarian Roman Catholic Religious Women and the “Persecuted Ones” -- tChapter 11 Denial and Defiance in the Work of Rabbi Regina Jonas -- tChapter 12 A Personal Account -- tIII. Aftermath: Politics, Faith, and Representation -- tChapter 13 Zionist and Israeli Attitudes Toward the Armenian Genocide -- tChapter 14 Faith, Religious Practices, and Genocide: Armenians and Jews in France following World War I and II -- tChapter 15 Orthodox Jewish Thought in the Wake of the Holocaust: Tamim Pa’alo of 1947 -- tChapter 16 Jewish-American Artists and the Holocaust: The Responses of Two Generations -- tChapter 17 The Journey to Poland -- tAFTERTHOUGHT Some Reflections on Genocide, Religion, and Modernity -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the widespread trends of secularization in the 20th century, religion has played an important role in several outbreaks of genocide since the First World War. And yet, not many scholars have looked either at the religious aspects of modern genocide, or at the manner in which religion has taken a position on mass killing. This collection of essays addresses this hiatus by examining the intersection between religion and state-organized murder in the cases of the Armenian, Jewish, Rwandan, and Bosnian genocides. Rather than a comprehensive overview, it offers a series of descrete, yet closely related case studies, that shed light on three fundamental aspects of this issue: the use of religion to legitimize and motivate genocide; the potential of religious faith to encourage physical and spiritual resistance to mass murder; and finally, the role of religion in coming to terms with the legacy of atrocity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGenocidexReligious aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and statexHistoryy20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Genocide & War Crimes.2bisacsh1 aAuron, Yair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaigell, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartov, Omer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/